Who's News:
   Citizens First Appoints
   Nichols as Chairman
   And Chief Executive
In the chief executive post, Mr. Nichols succeeds Rodney
T. Verblaauw, who will remain president. Messrs. Lyon and
Verblaauw will remain directors.
   Citizens First's earnings began to erode in 1989, and it
had a dismal 1990, reporting a loss of $102.4 million, or
$4.83 a share, when it took a $153 million loan-loss
provision. But for last year, it reported a profit of $3
million, or 13 cents a share, with a $24 million loss
provision.
   In the 1991 fourth quarter, Citizens First earned
$657,000, or three cents a share, compared with a net loss of
$64.3 million, or $3.03 a share, in the year-earlier period.
Assets declined 6% to $2.51 billion.